<subSubSection id="945526233C469DC7AD86618F9ED468C0" pageId="0" pageNumber="123" type="description">
<paragraph id="0E4CD40646D80B0CDBF2E5864C4B5946" pageId="0" pageNumber="123">Additional description.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="1D2AF1F5F134B6BF0CEAD0FC60BF61E0" pageId="0" pageNumber="123">
<emphasis id="72D15BE28168AC32E27E84A4BAEDEFCA" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="123">Male.</emphasis>
Antennomeres V-X with an area vested with sensilla basiconica at apical margin in ventral view; XI without pit-like sensillum. Elytra with two large callous areas at base. Tarsal pulvillar formula 4-4-2; protarsomeres I and II with large lobed pulvilli; III and IV with large bilobed pulvilli; mesotarsomers I with vestigial minute pulvillus; II with small lobed pulvillus; III and IV with small bilobed pulvilli; metatarsomeres I and II without pulvilli; III and IV with small bilobed pulvilli.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="6262B23E55EC62E1BDDFF2411AFB56D0" pageId="0" pageNumber="123">
Abdominal sternite V almost transverse. Pygidium weakly emarginated at apical margin (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="4C3F087D7A06DCE680563013750010C6" captionStart="Figures 36–40" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figures 36 - 40. Male terminal parts and aedeagus of Tillicera callosa 36 pygidium 37 ventrite VI 38 spicular fork 39 tegmen in lateral (a), ventral (b) and dorsal (c) views 40 median lobe in lateral (a), ventral (b), and dorsal (c) views." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1095.80097.figures36-40" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/672270" pageId="0" pageNumber="123">36</figureCitation>
); apical margin of ventrite VI (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="49D146CEFAA8702B7BA739A343B532F2" captionStart="Figures 36–40" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figures 36 - 40. Male terminal parts and aedeagus of Tillicera callosa 36 pygidium 37 ventrite VI 38 spicular fork 39 tegmen in lateral (a), ventral (b) and dorsal (c) views 40 median lobe in lateral (a), ventral (b), and dorsal (c) views." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1095.80097.figures36-40" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/672270" pageId="0" pageNumber="123">37</figureCitation>
) emarginated at middle; spicular forked, long (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="B8CD90A71642B6A32BA46F28CD08EE43" captionStart="Figures 36–40" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figures 36 - 40. Male terminal parts and aedeagus of Tillicera callosa 36 pygidium 37 ventrite VI 38 spicular fork 39 tegmen in lateral (a), ventral (b) and dorsal (c) views 40 median lobe in lateral (a), ventral (b), and dorsal (c) views." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1095.80097.figures36-40" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/672270" pageId="0" pageNumber="123">38</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="BC09DB006272BCDFED2691F50E7CFE53" pageId="0" pageNumber="123">
Tegmen (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="C6149E47CA8749B588C991B51394A28B" captionStart="Figures 36–40" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figures 36 - 40. Male terminal parts and aedeagus of Tillicera callosa 36 pygidium 37 ventrite VI 38 spicular fork 39 tegmen in lateral (a), ventral (b) and dorsal (c) views 40 median lobe in lateral (a), ventral (b), and dorsal (c) views." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1095.80097.figures36-40" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/672270" pageId="0" pageNumber="123">39a-c</figureCitation>
) with dorsal and ventral sinuses at apical 1/6 of total length; tegminal arms long, extending 1/3-2/3 of total length. Median lobe (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="C8163981DA4804E112077B72CCB01BE9" captionStart="Figures 36–40" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figures 36 - 40. Male terminal parts and aedeagus of Tillicera callosa 36 pygidium 37 ventrite VI 38 spicular fork 39 tegmen in lateral (a), ventral (b) and dorsal (c) views 40 median lobe in lateral (a), ventral (b), and dorsal (c) views." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1095.80097.figures36-40" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/672270" pageId="0" pageNumber="123">40a-c</figureCitation>
) longer than tegmen; plate simple, without denticles.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="ADC32D1D207855BE4D9B408A1914B130" pageId="0" pageNumber="123" type="remarks">
<paragraph id="6556CD5D94F90E968C4DD92E9B06EA98" pageId="0" pageNumber="123">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D0E56D68D6985C21A9827B0C193A0D3E" pageId="0" pageNumber="123">
This species was originally described based on a single female specimen from India. In this paper, we describe the male in detail. This species is also related to 
<taxonomicName id="62D6C74F7231716B33796EE978DA59A8" authority="Gorham, 1876" authorityName="Gorham" authorityYear="1876" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Hemitrachys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Hemitrachys bizonatus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="123" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bizonatus">
<emphasis id="A47B4D6AC4D2FC27A7403A1DA500DDDE" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="123">Hemitrachys bizonatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Gorham, 1876 based on the structure of the male genitalia.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
